00:00:10.764 --> 00:00:14.931
The basic equation of a capacitor,
says that the charge, Q,

00:00:15.892 --> 00:00:19.611
on a capacitor, is equal
to the capacitance value,

00:00:19.611 --> 00:00:22.592
times the voltage across the capacitor.

00:00:22.592 --> 00:00:24.841
Here's our capacitor over here.

00:00:24.841 --> 00:00:29.008
Let's say we have a voltage
on it, of plus or minus V.

00:00:31.433 --> 00:00:35.494
We say it has a capacitance value of C.

00:00:35.494 --> 00:00:38.457
That's a property of this device here.

00:00:38.457 --> 00:00:41.792
C is equal to, just looking
at the equation over there,

00:00:41.792 --> 00:00:43.939
C is equal to the ratio of the charge,

00:00:43.939 --> 00:00:45.967
stored in the capacitor, divided

00:00:45.967 --> 00:00:48.799
by the voltage of the capacitor.

00:00:48.799 --> 00:00:51.549
What we mean by stored charge is,

00:00:52.486 --> 00:00:54.437
if a current flows into this capacitor,

00:00:54.437 --> 00:00:57.521
it can leave some excess
charge on the top.

00:00:57.521 --> 00:00:59.524
I'll just mark that with plus signs.

00:00:59.524 --> 00:01:03.680
There will be a corresponding
set of minus charges,

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:06.680
on the other plate of the capacitor.

00:01:07.786 --> 00:01:11.869
This collection of
excess charge will be Q ,

00:01:12.752 --> 00:01:15.067
and this down here will be Q-,

00:01:15.067 --> 00:01:17.215
and they're gonna be the same value.

00:01:17.215 --> 00:01:19.855
What we say here, is when the
capacitor's in this state,

00:01:19.855 --> 00:01:23.229
we say it's storing this much charge.

00:01:23.229 --> 00:01:25.303
We'll just name one of these numbers here.

00:01:25.303 --> 00:01:27.920
They're gonna be the
same, with opposite signs.

00:01:27.920 --> 00:01:32.087
That's what it means for a
capacitor to store charge.

00:01:33.026 --> 00:01:35.743
What I want to do now, is
develop some sort of expression

00:01:35.743 --> 00:01:39.260
that relates the current
through a capacitor,

00:01:39.260 --> 00:01:40.255
to the voltage.

00:01:40.255 --> 00:01:43.588
We want to develop an IV characteristic,

00:01:45.007 --> 00:01:46.508
so this will correspond, sort of like,

00:01:46.508 --> 00:01:48.482
Ohm's Law for a capacitor.

00:01:48.482 --> 00:01:51.917
What relates the current to the voltage.

00:01:51.917 --> 00:01:55.114
The way I'm gonna do that,
is to exercise this equation,

00:01:55.114 --> 00:01:56.842
by causing some changes.

00:01:56.842 --> 00:02:01.416
In particular, we'll change
the voltage on this capacitor,

00:02:01.416 --> 00:02:04.244
and we'll see what happens over here.

00:02:04.244 --> 00:02:06.394
When we say we're gonna
change a voltage, that means

00:02:06.394 --> 00:02:10.561
we're gonna create something,
a condition of DV, DT.

00:02:12.045 --> 00:02:15.295
A change in voltage per change in time.

00:02:16.461 --> 00:02:17.896
I can do that by taking the derivative

00:02:17.896 --> 00:02:21.087
of both sides of this equation here.

00:02:21.087 --> 00:02:23.208
I've already done it for this side.

00:02:23.208 --> 00:02:26.208
Over here, what I'll have is DQ, DT.

00:02:29.367 --> 00:02:31.950
I took the derivative of
both sides, just to be sure

00:02:31.950 --> 00:02:35.271
I treated both sides of
the equation, the same.

00:02:35.271 --> 00:02:37.689
Let's look at this little
expression right here.

00:02:37.689 --> 00:02:39.090
This is kind of interesting.

00:02:39.090 --> 00:02:43.521
This is change of charge,
with change of time.

00:02:43.521 --> 00:02:47.521
That's equal to, that's
what we mean by current.

00:02:49.861 --> 00:02:50.860
That is current.

00:02:50.860 --> 00:02:53.193
The symbol for current is I.

00:02:55.718 --> 00:03:00.126
DQ, DT is current, essentially,
by definition, we give

00:03:00.126 --> 00:03:04.293
it the symbol I, and that's
gonna be equal to C DV, DT.

00:03:12.411 --> 00:03:14.610
This is an important equation.

00:03:14.610 --> 00:03:17.860
That's, basically, the IV relationship,

00:03:18.709 --> 00:03:22.376
between current and
voltage, in a capacitor.

00:03:23.471 --> 00:03:25.395
What it tells us, that the current

00:03:25.395 --> 00:03:27.345
is actually proportional to,

00:03:27.345 --> 00:03:30.333
and the proportionality constant is C,

00:03:30.333 --> 00:03:33.138
the current's proportional to
the rate of change of voltage.

00:03:33.138 --> 00:03:34.278
Not the voltage itself,

00:03:34.278 --> 00:03:38.112
but to the rate of change of voltage.

00:03:38.112 --> 00:03:41.482
Now, what I want to do
is find a expression

00:03:41.482 --> 00:03:44.026
that expresses V, in terms of I.

00:03:44.026 --> 00:03:47.276
Here we have I, in terms of DV, DT.

00:03:47.276 --> 00:03:49.362
Let's figure out if we can express V,

00:03:49.362 --> 00:03:52.891
in terms of some expression containing I.

00:03:52.891 --> 00:03:53.724
The way I do that is, I need

00:03:53.724 --> 00:03:56.123
to eliminate this derivative here.

00:03:56.123 --> 00:03:59.505
I'm gonna do that by taking
the integral of this side

00:03:59.505 --> 00:04:01.925
of the equation, and at
the same time, I'll take

00:04:01.925 --> 00:04:03.117
the integral of the other side

00:04:03.117 --> 00:04:05.817
of the equation, to keep everything equal.

00:04:05.817 --> 00:04:09.567
What that looks like
is, the integral of I...

00:04:13.074 --> 00:04:16.907
With respect to time,
is equal to the integral

00:04:18.809 --> 00:04:21.976
